english:
  title: Inscription on the Clepsydra Pavilion, with Preface
  author: Kim Bin
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In imperial governance, nothing weighs more heavily than harmonizing the seasons and rectifying the calendar. Yet such verification depends upon the celestial instruments and the water-clock. For without instruments, one cannot observe the movements of heaven and earth; without the clepsydra, one cannot determine the boundaries of day and night. Millennia are built upon the foundation of a single moment without error, and the flourishing of all endeavors springs from not wasting a single breath of time. Thus, the sage-kings and enlightened rulers of every age, in accordance with heaven's way, have shown reverence to these instruments without fail.

    I humbly consider that Your Majesty possesses the reverent heart of the Emperor Yao and embodies the wisdom of the great Shun who studied the celestial sphere. Therefore, you have commanded the artisans to craft new instruments for observation and to renew the water-clock to align with the sundial. Thus, within the western reaches of the palace, a pavilion of three bays has been erected. The protector-general Jang Yeong-sil was commanded to create wooden automata—three deities and twelve hour-beings—to replace the duty of the rooster-callers.

    In the eastern bay, two-tiered seating was arranged: the three deities occupy the upper tier, one before a bell to announce the hour by striking, one before a drum to announce the watch by beating, one before a gong to announce the moment by tapping. The twelve hour-beings each hold plaques inscribed with their hours, standing around the great wheel, hidden below the middle tier, ascending in turn as time unfolds. In the central bay, a water vessel is set with ingenious mechanisms, using iron pellets to trigger the machinery. At each appointed hour, the deities respond in unison. Comparing with the heavenly instruments, they accord perfectly, as though guarded by spirits themselves. All who witness it marvel in astonishment. Truly, this is a magnificent system never before seen in our eastern realm.

    Thus the pavilion is named the Clepsydra Reporter. I am commanded by the sovereign to make this known to future generations. I, your minister, bow and present this inscription:

    Yin and yang succeed each other in turn,
    Day and night interweave and shift—
    Heaven's way moves in silent operation,
    The spirits' work leaves not a trace.

    By gathering and distributing forces,
    The water-clock was brought to being,
    First created in the Yellow Emperor's age,
    Each era has refined its method.

    Only in our eastern land
    Did the ancient systems lie dormant and sparse,
    But the new design, now perfected,
    Comes from our sovereign's penetrating wisdom.

    First studying the celestial sphere,
    Then renewing the clepsydra's art—
    Four vessels pour forth their waters,
    Two vessels receive their flow.

    The passage of day and night
    Begins with each incremental moment.
    Rods are raised to mark the twelve,
    When the mechanism strikes, there is no error.

    Wood is carved to form the spirits,
    No laborer need guard the watch—
    The deities take charge of time's flow,
    The tall pavilion now stands complete.

    Upper and lower seats arranged,
    Placed within the eastern bay:
    Three deities dwell above,
    Ringing bell, drum, and gong in sequence,
    Replacing the rooster-caller's cry
    With sounds that mark each hour's turn.

    Twelve hour-beings stationed below
    Hold their plaques of the zodiac signs,
    Circling the great wheel's face,
    Ascending in turn to announce the time.

    Where the mechanisms engage and clash—
    In the central bay it is proven—
    Layered platforms bridge the span,
    Vessels connected, passing on the flow.

    Two bronze plates, precisely fashioned,
    Holes pierced like arrows' paths,
    Machinery installed to receive iron pellets,
    Mounted upon the vessel's face.

    When the arrow rises, the mechanism stirs,
    The pellet falls and rolls its course,
    On a slanting path it travels,
    Striking the deity below.

    The double path divides to four,
    Like roads that branch and lead all ways,
    Connected tubes left and right
    Receive the cascading pellets' flow.

    Tubes contain their gated holes,
    Matched precisely to the bronze plates' count,
    Greater pellets separately arrayed
    Along the tubes' edge, waiting near.

    Each in turn they strike the mechanism,
    Swift as lightning's flash—
    Wherever the gears engage and touch,
    The hour-keepers fulfill their duty,

    As though by spirits' hands they move,
    All who see it stand amazed.
    What majesty in this grand design!
    It follows heaven's way and sets the rule,

    Its system mirrors creation's harmony,
    Its bounds accord with nature's measure.
    Consider how each precious moment
    Brings about all human work:

    Though we cut the willow for a fence,
    The people need not doubt or stray.
    Thus we establish this standard measure,
    Revealing it to ages yet unborn.
  footnotes:
    - The 'celestial sphere' (璇璣玉衡) traditionally refers to Yao and Shun's methods of astronomical observation, considered the golden age of accurate timekeeping.
    - The 'rooster-callers' (鷄人) were traditionally official timekeepers in East Asian courts, whose role this mechanical apparatus replaces.
    - Jang Yeong-sil was a celebrated Korean inventor and engineer of the Joseon period, famous for creating advanced astronomical and timekeeping instruments.
    - The twelve hour-beings represent the twelve zodiacal hours of the traditional East Asian timekeeping system.
